<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14 is: The Standard Library function memcmp shall not be used to compare null terminated strings.

</misra_rule>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- is_rule_violated: whether the rule is violated or not (true/false),
- scenario: a specific violation scenario.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext:
```c
bool OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext(OS_object_iter_t *iter)
{
    OS_common_record_t *record;
    bool                got_next;

    got_next           = false;
    iter->token.obj_id = OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED;

    do
    {
        ++iter->token.obj_idx;
        if (iter->token.obj_idx >= iter->limit)
        {
            break;
        }

        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(iter->base, iter->token);
        if (iter->match == NULL || iter->match(iter->arg, &iter->token, record))
        {
            iter->token.obj_id = record->active_id;
            got_next           = true;
        }
    } while (!got_next);

    return got_next;
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext:
static inline osal_index_t OS_ObjectIndexFromToken(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    return token->obj_idx;
}
...
osal_id_t obj_id
</additional code>
<target_code>
Here is the code fragment that you need to analyze:
```c
record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(iter->base, iter->token);
```
Focus on the above code fragment and judge whether it violates the rule 21.14 or not.
</target_code>
scenario: The fragment simply reads a table element via the macro/function OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(iter->base, iter->token). There is no call to memcmp nor any string comparison in this line. Therefore the rule is not violated. (Caveat: if the implementation of OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or code it expands to internally used memcmp to compare null‑terminated strings, that internal use would violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14 — but no such use is visible in the provided fragment.)
